-- в”Ђв”Ђ Home Assistant в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source, self-hosted smart home platform that unifies over 1,000 device integrations under local, privacy-focused control.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source (optional Cloud subscription)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free; Home Assistant Cloud from $6.50/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Home Assistant Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Home Assistant review 2026: explore this open-source smart home platform's 1,000+ integrations, local control, pricing and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Home Assistant is a free and open-source smart home automation platform originally created by Paulus Schoutsen, who started the project as a personal Python application in September 2013 to control a smart lighting system without depending on any proprietary vendor platform, then published it publicly on GitHub in November 2013. Over the following decade it grew into one of the most active open-source software projects on GitHub, now automating more than a million homes with over 2 million active users and support for more than 1,000 individual device and service integrations spanning protocols like Zigbee, Z-Wave, Matter, Thread and Wi-Fi, plus thousands of cloud services and smart devices from virtually every major manufacturer. Because Home Assistant is entirely open source, it has no traditional venture-backed funding history in the way commercial software companies do; instead, its sustainability rests on a commercial companion company, Nabu Casa, Inc, which Schoutsen and the core Home Assistant team founded in September 2018, headquartered in Irvine, California. Nabu Casa's sole revenue source is its optional 'Home Assistant Cloud' subscription service, and all of that revenue is reinvested into funding full-time engineers who work on Home Assistant, the companion ESPHome firmware project for DIY smart devices, and Home Assistant OS, plus official hardware products such as the Home Assistant Green and Yellow devices. In 2024, the project's governance was formalized under the Open Home Foundation, a nonprofit organization founded by Schoutsen (who serves as its president) to serve as the official parent and steward of Home Assistant, ESPHome and related open-source projects, ensuring the platform remains independent of any single company's commercial interests. Architecturally, Home Assistant is designed around local control: unlike many commercial smart home hubs that route device commands through a manufacturer's cloud servers, Home Assistant runs entirely on hardware the user controls, whether a Raspberry Pi, a dedicated mini PC, a virtual machine, or official Home Assistant Green/Yellow hardware, and processes automations locally by default, which improves privacy, reliability during internet outages, and response latency. Its core features include a customizable dashboard interface built on the Lovelace UI framework, a powerful automation and scripting engine for creating conditional rules across any connected device, an add-on system managed through the Home Assistant Supervisor for extending functionality (such as adding a media server or additional integrations), a community-maintained extension marketplace called HACS (Home Assistant Community Store) for custom integrations and dashboard cards not included in the core distribution, native energy monitoring dashboards for tracking electricity, gas and solar production, and Assist, a local, privacy-focused voice assistant framework that lets users control their home by voice without routing audio to Amazon or Google, part of the project's ongoing 'Year of the Voice' initiative to reduce dependence on big tech voice assistants. Official companion mobile apps for iOS and Android provide remote dashboard access, location-based automation triggers and push notifications. Home Assistant's core software is entirely free to download, install and use indefinitely with no feature restrictions or paywalls, since the project is open source. The only paid component is the optional Nabu Casa Home Assistant Cloud subscription, priced at approximately $6.50 per month or $65 per year, which adds convenience features that would otherwise require manual network configuration: secure remote access to a home's Home Assistant instance from anywhere without port forwarding, automated encrypted cloud backups, and one-click integration with Amazon Alexa and Google Assistant voice control. Home Assistant's target audience includes technically inclined smart home hobbyists, privacy-focused users who want to avoid sending home data to manufacturer clouds, and DIY electronics enthusiasts building custom sensors and automations. Its main competitors and alternatives include commercial hub ecosystems like Samsung SmartThings, Apple HomeKit and Google Home, as well as other self-hosted or prosumer platforms such as Hubitat and openHAB; Home Assistant differentiates itself through the sheer breadth of its integration library, its fully local-first architecture, its transparent nonprofit governance under the Open Home Foundation, and its complete freedom from any advertising or data-monetization business model.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'caf4aea6-fd20-4af6-9d16-4a5cbc4d2503';

